.SH NAME
Net::Nostr::RelayStore \- Indexed in\-memory event storage for Nostr relays
.SH SYNOPSIS
.IX Header "SYNOPSIS"
.Vb 1
\&    use Net::Nostr::RelayStore;
\&
\&    my $store = Net::Nostr::RelayStore\->new(max_events => 10000);
\&
\&    $store\->store($event);                          # returns 1 (new) or 0 (duplicate)
\&    my $event = $store\->get_by_id($id);             # or undef
\&    my $old   = $store\->find_replaceable($pk, $k);  # or undef
\&    my $addr  = $store\->find_addressable($pk, $k, $d);  # or undef
\&    $store\->delete_by_id($id);                      # returns removed event or undef
\&    $store\->delete_matching($pk, \e@ids, \e@addrs, $ts);  # NIP\-09
\&
\&    my $results = $store\->query(\e@filters);          # sorted, deduped, limit\-aware
\&    my $count   = $store\->count(\e@filters);          # deduped count
\&
\&    my $all = $store\->all_events;                    # snapshot copy, sorted
\&    my $n   = $store\->event_count;
\&    $store\->clear;
.Ve
.SH DESCRIPTION
.IX Header "DESCRIPTION"
Provides indexed in\-memory event storage for Net::Nostr::Relay. Events
are indexed by id, pubkey, kind, pubkey+kind (replaceable), pubkey+kind+d_tag
(addressable), and tag values. Queries use the narrowest applicable index
as the candidate set, then post\-filter with "matches" in Net::Nostr::Filter.
.PP
This is the default storage backend. Third\-party backends (SQLite, LMDB, etc.)
can implement the same method interface and be passed to Net::Nostr::Relay
via the \f(CW\*(C`store\*(C'\fR constructor option.
.SH CONSTRUCTOR
.IX Header "CONSTRUCTOR"
.SS new
.IX Subsection "new"
.Vb 2
\&    my $store = Net::Nostr::RelayStore\->new;
\&    my $store = Net::Nostr::RelayStore\->new(max_events => 5000);
.Ve
.PP
Strict constructor. Creates a new empty store. All arguments are optional.
Croaks on unknown arguments or invalid \f(CW\*(C`max_events\*(C'\fR values.
.IP max_events 4
.IX Item "max_events"
Maximum number of events to retain. When exceeded, the oldest event (by
\&\f(CW\*(C`created_at\*(C'\fR) is evicted. Must be a positive integer. Defaults to unlimited.
.SH METHODS
.IX Header "METHODS"
.SS store
.IX Subsection "store"
.Vb 1
\&    my $ok = $store\->store($event);
.Ve
.PP
Stores an event. Returns 1 on success, 0 if the event is a duplicate (same
id already stored). Updates all indexes. If \f(CW\*(C`max_events\*(C'\fR is set and the
store exceeds capacity after insertion, the oldest event is evicted.
.PP
For replaceable events (kind 0, 3, 10000\-19999), the \f(CW\*(C`find_replaceable\*(C'\fR
index always points to the newest event by \f(CW\*(C`created_at\*(C'\fR, with lowest \f(CW\*(C`id\*(C'\fR
as tiebreak. Storing an older replaceable event adds it to the store but
does not overwrite the index entry. The same applies to addressable events
(kind 30000\-39999) via \f(CW\*(C`find_addressable\*(C'\fR.
.PP
.Vb 2
\&    $store\->store($event);  # 1
\&    $store\->store($event);  # 0 (duplicate)
.Ve
.SS get_by_id
.IX Subsection "get_by_id"
.Vb 1
\&    my $event = $store\->get_by_id($event_id);
.Ve
.PP
Returns the event with the given id, or \f(CW\*(C`undef\*(C'\fR if not found.
.SS find_replaceable
.IX Subsection "find_replaceable"
.Vb 1
\&    my $event = $store\->find_replaceable($pubkey, $kind);
.Ve
.PP
Returns the newest stored replaceable event for the given pubkey and kind,
or \f(CW\*(C`undef\*(C'\fR if none exists. When the store holds multiple versions (e.g.
an older event not yet cleaned up by the relay), this always returns the
one with the highest \f(CW\*(C`created_at\*(C'\fR (lowest \f(CW\*(C`id\*(C'\fR as tiebreak).
Replaceable kinds are 0, 3, and 10000\-19999.
.SS find_addressable
.IX Subsection "find_addressable"
.Vb 1
\&    my $event = $store\->find_addressable($pubkey, $kind, $d_tag);
.Ve
.PP
Returns the newest stored addressable event for the given pubkey, kind,
and d tag, or \f(CW\*(C`undef\*(C'\fR if none exists. When the store holds multiple
versions, this always returns the one with the highest \f(CW\*(C`created_at\*(C'\fR
(lowest \f(CW\*(C`id\*(C'\fR as tiebreak). Addressable kinds are 30000\-39999.
.SS delete_by_id
.IX Subsection "delete_by_id"
.Vb 1
\&    my $removed = $store\->delete_by_id($event_id);
.Ve
.PP
Removes the event with the given id from all indexes. Returns the removed
event, or \f(CW\*(C`undef\*(C'\fR if not found. If the removed event was the current entry
in the replaceable or addressable index, the next best candidate (by
\&\f(CW\*(C`created_at\*(C'\fR DESC, \f(CW\*(C`id\*(C'\fR ASC) is promoted. If no candidates remain, the
index entry is cleared.
.SS delete_matching
.IX Subsection "delete_matching"
.Vb 1
\&    my $count = $store\->delete_matching($pubkey, \e@ids, \e@addresses, $before_ts);
.Ve
.PP
NIP\-09 bulk deletion. Deletes events owned by \f(CW$pubkey\fR by event id or by
coordinate. Addresses may be addressable (\f(CW"kind:pubkey:d_tag"\fR) or
replaceable (\f(CW"kind:pubkey:"\fR with empty d_tag). Both id\-based and
address\-based deletions skip events belonging to a different pubkey.
Address\-based deletion additionally only removes events with
\&\f(CW\*(C`created_at <= $before_ts\*(C'\fR. Kind 5 (deletion) events are never deleted.
Returns the number of events deleted.
.PP
.Vb 3
\&    $store\->delete_matching($pk, [$event_id], [], 9999);
\&    $store\->delete_matching($pk, [], ["30023:$pk:slug"], $deletion_ts);
\&    $store\->delete_matching($pk, [], ["10000:$pk:"], $deletion_ts);  # replaceable
.Ve
.SS query
.IX Subsection "query"
.Vb 1
\&    my $events = $store\->query(\e@filters);
.Ve
.PP
Returns an arrayref of events matching any of the given filters (OR across
filters, AND within each filter). Results are sorted by \f(CW\*(C`created_at\*(C'\fR DESC
then \f(CW\*(C`id\*(C'\fR ASC. Expired events (NIP\-40) are excluded. Events matching
multiple filters are deduplicated. Each filter\*(Aqs \f(CW\*(C`limit\*(C'\fR is respected
independently. A \f(CW\*(C`limit\*(C'\fR of 0 returns no events for that filter.
.PP
.Vb 4
\&    my $results = $store\->query([
\&        Net::Nostr::Filter\->new(kinds => [1], limit => 10),
\&        Net::Nostr::Filter\->new(authors => [$pk]),
\&    ]);
.Ve
.SS count
.IX Subsection "count"
.Vb 1
\&    my $n = $store\->count(\e@filters);
.Ve
.PP
Like "query" but returns only the count. Deduplicates across filters
and skips expired events.
.SS all_events
.IX Subsection "all_events"
.Vb 1
\&    my $events = $store\->all_events;
.Ve
.PP
Returns a snapshot (array copy) of all stored events, sorted by
\&\f(CW\*(C`created_at\*(C'\fR DESC then \f(CW\*(C`id\*(C'\fR ASC. Mutating the returned arrayref does
not affect the store. Unlike "query", this includes expired events.
.SS event_count
.IX Subsection "event_count"
.Vb 1
\&    my $n = $store\->event_count;
.Ve
.PP
Returns the number of events currently stored.
.SS max_events
.IX Subsection "max_events"
.Vb 1
\&    my $max = $store\->max_events;  # positive integer or undef
.Ve
.PP
Returns the configured maximum event capacity, or \f(CW\*(C`undef\*(C'\fR if unlimited.
.SS clear
.IX Subsection "clear"
.Vb 1
\&    $store\->clear;
.Ve
.PP
Removes all events and resets all indexes.
.SH "PLUGGABLE BACKENDS"
.IX Header "PLUGGABLE BACKENDS"
Third\-party storage backends should implement the same public method interface:
\&\f(CW\*(C`store\*(C'\fR, \f(CW\*(C`get_by_id\*(C'\fR, \f(CW\*(C`find_replaceable\*(C'\fR, \f(CW\*(C`find_addressable\*(C'\fR,
\&\f(CW\*(C`delete_by_id\*(C'\fR, \f(CW\*(C`delete_matching\*(C'\fR, \f(CW\*(C`query\*(C'\fR, \f(CW\*(C`count\*(C'\fR, \f(CW\*(C`all_events\*(C'\fR,
\&\f(CW\*(C`event_count\*(C'\fR, and \f(CW\*(C`clear\*(C'\fR. No base class or role is required \-\- the
interface is duck\-typed.
